static-ip
The previous Ubuntu 17 versions were using ifconfig and its configuration file /etc/network/interfaces to configure the network.

$ sudo vi /etc/network/interfaces
 auto eth0
 iface eth0 inet static
 address 192.168.1.10
 netmask 255.255.255.0
 network 192.168.1.0
 broadcast 192.168.1.255
 gateway 192.168.1.1


$ sudo /etc/init.d/networking restart

$ sudo ifconfig eth0 down 
$ sudo ifconfig eth0 up


Configuring Static IP address on Ubuntu Server #
On Ubuntu 20.04

sudo vi /etc/cloud/cloud.cfg.d/99-disable-network-config.cfg
/etc/cloud/cloud.cfg.d/99-disable-network-config.cfg
network: {config: disabled}



To assign a static IP address on the network interface, open the YAML configuration file with your text editor :


sudo vi /etc/netplan/01-netcfg.yaml
/etc/netplan/01-netcfg.yaml
network:
  version: 2
  renderer: networkd
  ethernets:
    ens3:
      dhcp4: yes
Copy


network:
  version: 2
  renderer: networkd
  ethernets:
    eth0:
      dhcp4: no
      addresses:
        - 192.168.1.220/24
      gateway4: 192.168.121.1
      nameservers:
          addresses: [8.8.8.8, 1.1.1.1]